There are four recognized climate types in the Philippines, and they are based on the distribution of rainfall ''(See the Philippine Climate Map at the top)''.{{efn|1=  This classification was first established by {{harvnb|Coronas|1920|pages=68–72}} and then slightly modified by PAGASA ({{harvnb|Flores|Balagot|1969}}; {{harvnb|Kintanar|1984}}).}}  They are described as follows:<ref name=Seasons />
{|
|
*{{hsp}}
| style="text-align:left;" | '''Type Ⅰ'''
| style="text-align:left;" |  Two pronounced seasons: dry from November to April and wet during the rest of the year.
|- 
|
*{{hsp}}
| style="text-align:left;" | '''Type Ⅱ'''
| style="text-align:left;" | No dry season with a pronounced rainfall from November to January.
|-
|
*{{hsp}}
| style="text-align:left;" | '''Type Ⅲ'''
| style="text-align:left;" |  Seasons are not very pronounced, relatively dry from November to April, and wet during the rest of the year.
|-
|
*{{hsp}}
| style="text-align:left;" | '''Type Ⅳ'''
| style="text-align:left;" |  Rainfall is more or less evenly distributed throughout the year.
|}

