In the [[Byzantine Empire]], a '''''kleisoura''''' ({{lang-el|κλεισούρα}}, "enclosure, defile") was a term traditionally applied to a fortified [[mountain pass]] and the military district protecting it.<ref name="Kazhdan-Ahrweiler">{{harvnb|Kazhdan|1991|p=1132}}; {{harvnb|Glykatzi-Ahrweiler|1960|pp=1–111}}.</ref> By the late 7th century, it came to be applied to more extensive frontier districts, distinct from the larger ''[[Theme (Byzantine district)|thema]]ta'', chiefly along the Empire's eastern border with the [[Caliphate]] along the line of the [[Taurus Mountains|Taurus]]-[[Anti-Taurus Mountains|Anti-Taurus]] mountains (in the [[Balkans|West]], only [[Strymon (theme)|Strymon]] was in its early days termed a ''kleisoura'').<ref name="Kazhdan-Ahrweiler"/> A ''kleisoura'' or ''kleisourarchia'' was an autonomous command, under a '''''kleisourarches''''' (Greek: κλεισουράρχης). Eventually, most ''kleisourai'' were raised to full ''themata'', and the term fell out of use after the 10th century (in late Byzantine times, ''[[droungos]]'' had a similar meaning). Its [[Islam]]ic counterpart in [[Cilicia]] and [[Al Jazira, Mesopotamia|Mesopotamia]] was the ''[[thughur|al-thughūr]]''.<ref name="Kazhdan-Ahrweiler"/>

